                "id": "e2945cab-bb7e-4a48-a59b-80814a0a0fe4",
                "role": "assistant",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "kind": "text",
                    "data": "This is exactly the UNC path error — you're still using the **Windows** `npm`/`node`, which can't operate on WSL paths. The project must be installed and run from inside WSL.\n\n**Do this:**\n\n1. Open the **Ubuntu** app (or any WSL terminal) from the Windows Start menu — not PowerShell, not CMD, not Windows Terminal running PowerShell.\n\n2. Inside the Ubuntu terminal, run:\n```bash\ncd ~/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology\nnpm install\nnpm run dev\n```\n\n3. Open `http://localhost:5173` in your browser.\n\n---\n\n**Why this happens:** When you open a file explorer path like `\\\\wsl.localhost\\Ubuntu-24.04\\...` and run npm from there, Windows uses its own `node.exe` and `npm.cmd`. esbuild (used by Vite) runs a post-install script via `cmd.exe`, and `cmd.exe` refuses to use UNC paths as the working directory — so it falls back to `C:\\Windows` and can't find `install.js`.\n\nThe fix is always to run from *inside* WSL, where the Linux node/npm handle everything natively.\n\n---\n\nIf you don't have Node.js installed inside WSL yet, run this first in the Ubuntu terminal:\n\n```bash\n# Install nvm (Node Version Manager)\ncurl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.39.7/install.sh | bash\nsource ~/.bashrc\n\n# Install Node 20 LTS\nnvm install 20\nnvm use 20\n\n# Then install and run the project\ncd ~/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology\nnpm install\nnpm run dev\n```"
                  }
                ],
                "meta": {
                  "timestamp": 1783331089
                }
              }
            },
