    {
      "version": "v1",
      "kind": "AssistantMessage",
      "data": {
        "message_id": "4f1cc4cb-39e6-4942-8334-2c08d1d64b7a",
        "content": [
          {
            "kind": "text",
            "data": "This is exactly the UNC path error — you're still using the **Windows** `npm`/`node`, which can't operate on WSL paths. The project must be installed and run from inside WSL.\n\n**Do this:**\n\n1. Open the **Ubuntu** app (or any WSL terminal) from the Windows Start menu — not PowerShell, not CMD, not Windows Terminal running PowerShell.\n\n2. Inside the Ubuntu terminal, run:\n```bash\ncd ~/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology\nnpm install\nnpm run dev\n```\n\n3. Open `http://localhost:5173` in your browser.\n\n---\n\n**Why this happens:** When you open a file explorer path like `\\\\wsl.localhost\\Ubuntu-24.04\\...` and run npm from there, Windows uses its own `node.exe` and `npm.cmd`. esbuild (used by Vite) runs a post-install script via `cmd.exe`, and `cmd.exe` refuses to use UNC paths as the working directory — so it falls back to `C:\\Windows` and can't find `install.js`.\n\nThe fix is always to run from *inside* WSL, where the Linux node/npm handle everything natively.\n\n---\n\nIf you don't have Node.js installed inside WSL yet, run this first in the Ubuntu terminal:\n\n```bash\n# Install nvm (Node Version Manager)\ncurl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.39.7/install.sh | bash\nsource ~/.bashrc\n\n# Install Node 20 LTS\nnvm install 20\nnvm use 20\n\n# Then install and run the project\ncd ~/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology\nnpm install\nnpm run dev\n```"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "version": "v1",
      "kind": "Prompt",
      "data": {
        "message_id": "f0e06080-7034-4668-9ea0-d43d9e7e67bc",
        "content": [
          {
            "kind": "text",
            "data": "jose@DESKTOP-M6UEM1K:~/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology$ npm install\n\nadded 6 packages, removed 40 packages, changed 2 packages, and audited 21 packages in 803ms\n\n3 packages are looking for funding\n  run `npm fund` for details\n\n2 vulnerabilities (1 moderate, 1 high)\n\nTo address all issues (including breaking changes), run:\n  npm audit fix --force\n\nRun `npm audit` for details.\njose@DESKTOP-M6UEM1K:~/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology$ npm audit fix --force\nnpm warn using --force Recommended protections disabled.\nnpm warn audit Updating vite to 8.1.3, which is a SemVer major change.\nnpm error code ENOTEMPTY\nnpm error syscall rename\nnpm error path /home/jose/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology/node_modules/esbuild\nnpm error dest /home/jose/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology/node_modules/.esbuild-dK0yaSN9\nnpm error errno -39\nnpm error ENOTEMPTY: directory not empty, rename '/home/jose/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology/node_modules/esbuild' -> '/home/jose/Simulador_topologia_red/network-topology/node_modules/.esbuild-dK0yaSN9'\nnpm error A complete log of this run can be found in: /home/jose/.npm/_logs/2026-07-06T09_51_07_350Z-debug-0.log"
          }
        ],
        "meta": {
          "timestamp": 1783331482
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "version": "v1",
      "kind": "AssistantMessage",
      "data": {
        "message_id": "612fda89-e386-4b27-b1f1-1e56601e75ae",
        "content": [
          {
            "kind": "text",
            "data": "The `npm install` succeeded — that's all you need. The audit fix error is a separate issue from running a half-installed `node_modules` left over from the Windows attempt conflicting with the rename. Don't worry about it.\n\nJust clean up and reinstall cleanly:\n\n```bash\nrm -rf node_modules\nnpm install\nnpm run dev\n```\n\nThat will give you a clean install from WSL with no leftover Windows artifacts, and then start the dev server."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
