                    "path": "network-topology/README.md",
                    "content": "# Network Topology Visualizer\n\nAn interactive 3D network topology viewer built with **Three.js** and **TypeScript**, bundled by **Vite**.\n\n---\n\n## Features\n\n- 6 selectable network topologies extracted from academic material (see [Topologies](#topologies) below)\n- Left sidebar to switch between topologies instantly\n- Right panel showing a full description and feature table for the active topology\n- 3D scene with orbit controls (rotate, zoom, pan)\n- Four node types with distinct geometries and colors: **Router** (octahedron), **Switch** (box), **Server** (cylinder), **Client** (sphere)\n- Hover tooltip showing node id, type, and status\n- Animated nodes (gentle float + router spin) and pulsing ambient light\n- Legend panel and controls hint overlay\n\n---\n\n## Topologies\n\nAll topologies are defined in `src/topologies.ts` and described in `src/topologyMeta.ts`. Each one displays a feature table in the UI derived from the academic source (Tema 4 — Redes de interconexión).\n\n### Malla (Mesh) — k-ary 2-mesh\n\nA regular 2D grid of switches, each connected to its orthogonal neighbours. The most common direct topology.\n\n| Property | Value |\n|----------|-------|\n| Type | Direct, regular, orthogonal |\n| Switches | k² (default 4×4 = 16) |\n| Switch degree | 2–4 (varies at edges/corners) |\n| Max hop count | 2(k−1) |\n| Symmetric | No (except hypercube) |\n| Homogeneous | No |\n| Typical routing | DOR (XY routing) |\n\n### Toroide (Torus) — k-ary 2-cube\n\nA mesh with wrap-around links in each dimension. Reduces hop count, increases bisection bandwidth and fault tolerance compared to the equivalent mesh.\n\n| Property | Value |\n|----------|-------|\n| Type | Direct, regular, orthogonal |\n| Switches | k² (default 4×4 = 16) |\n| Switch degree | 4 (uniform — fully homogeneous) |\n| Max hop count | ⌊k/2⌋ × 2 |\n| Symmetric | Yes |\n| Homogeneous | Yes |\n| Typical routing | DOR, XY-YX with virtual channels |\n\n### WK-Recursiva\n\nBuilt by recursively replicating a base virtual node (a clique of k nodes). Level-l virtual nodes are composed of k level-(l−1) virtual nodes connected via their free ports.\n\n| Property | Value |\n|----------|-------|\n| Type | Direct, regular, non-orthogonal |\n| Parameters | k (clique size), l (expansion level) |\n| Total nodes | k^l (default k=4, l=2 → 16) |\n| Switch degree | (k−1) intra-group + 1 inter-group |\n| Symmetric | Yes (within level) |\n| Typical routing | Recursive / hierarchical |\n\n### Fat Tree — k-ary n-tree\n\nAn indirect topology based on a complete tree that grows wider (higher bandwidth) towards the root. Belongs to the bMIN family (bidirectional Multistage Interconnection Network). Only leaf-level switches connect to endpoint nodes.\n\n| Property | Value |\n|----------|-------|\n| Type | Indirect, regular, multistage |\n| Parameters | k (degree), n (stages) |\n| Switches | k^n − 1 (default k=2, n=4 → 15) |\n| Endpoint nodes | k^(n−1) × k |\n| Max hop count | 2(n−1) |\n| Homogeneous | No (degree varies per stage) |\n| Typical routing | Up-Down (up*/down*) |\n\n### Flattened Butterfly\n\nAn evolution of the butterfly topology where switches in each column are collapsed into a single higher-degree switch. Delivers the same bisection bandwidth as the original butterfly but with lower hop count, at the cost of a higher switch degree.\n\n| Property | Value |\n|----------|-------|\n| Type | Direct, regular, orthogonal |\n| Parameters | p rows, q columns |\n| Switches | p × q (default 4×4 = 16) |\n| Switch degree | (q−1) + (p−1) |\n| Max hop count | 2 |\n| Symmetric | Yes |\n| Homogeneous | Yes |\n| Typical routing | Dimension Order, adaptive |\n\n### Bus (Medio Compartido)\n\nThe simplest shared-medium network. All nodes share the same medium; only one device can transmit at a time. Lowest implementation cost but bandwidth degrades quickly with node count.\n\n| Property | Value |\n|----------|-------|\n| Type | Shared medium |\n| Node degree | 1 |\n| Max hop count | 2 (src → bus → dst) |\n| Fault tolerance | Very low (single point of failure) |\n| Duplex mode | Half-duplex or Full-duplex |\n| Typical routing | Broadcast (filter by destination) |\n\n---\n\n## Prerequisites\n\n| Tool | Minimum version |\n|------|----------------|\n| Node.js | 18.x or later |\n| npm | 9.x or later (bundled with Node 18) |\n\n> Verify with `node -v` and `npm -v`.\n\n---\n\n## Project Structure\n\n```\nnetwork-topology/\n├── index.html                   # HTML entry point\n├── package.json                 # Dependencies and npm scripts\n├── tsconfig.json                # TypeScript compiler options\n├── vite.config.ts               # Vite bundler config\n└── src/\n    ├── main.ts                  # Scene, lighting, topology switching, animation loop\n    ├── NetworkGraph.ts          # Graph manager — addNode / addLink / clear / update\n    ├── NetworkNode.ts           # Node class — 4 types, 3 statuses, label sprites\n    ├── NetworkLink.ts           # Edge class — 3 link statuses, live geometry update\n    ├── Tooltip.ts               # Hover tooltip DOM element\n    ├── TopologySelector.ts      # Left sidebar — buttons for each topology\n    ├── TopologyInfo.ts          # Right panel — description + features table\n    ├── topologies.ts            # Generator functions for each topology\n    ├── topologyMeta.ts          # Metadata, feature tables, and generator registry\n    └── style.css                # Full dark-theme layout\n```\n\n---\n\n## Setup & Running\n\n### 1. Clone or download the project\n\n```bash\ngit clone <repo-url>\ncd network-topology\n```\n\nOr simply navigate to the directory if you already have the files:\n\n```bash\ncd network-topology\n```\n\n### 2. Install dependencies\n\n```bash\nnpm install\n```\n\n> **Windows + WSL users:** if the project files live inside the WSL filesystem (`/home/...`),\n> you **must** run all `npm` commands from a **WSL terminal** (e.g. Ubuntu), not from\n> Windows PowerShell or CMD. Opening a WSL terminal and navigating to the project path with\n> `cd /home/<user>/...` is the simplest way to avoid UNC path errors.\n\nThis installs:\n- `three` — 3D rendering engine\n- `vite` — fast dev server and bundler\n- `typescript` — type-checker\n- `@types/three` — Three.js type definitions\n\n### 3. Start the development server\n\n```bash\nnpm run dev\n```\n\nVite will print a local URL (usually `http://localhost:5173`). Open it in any modern browser.\n\n### 4. (Optional) Build for production\n\n```bash\nnpm run build\n```\n\nThe optimised output is written to `dist/`. Serve it with any static file host:\n\n```bash\nnpm run preview   # preview the production build locally\n```\n\n---\n\n## Controls\n\n| Action | Input |\n|--------|-------|\n| Switch topology | Click a button in the left sidebar |\n| Rotate scene | Left-click + drag |\n| Zoom | Mouse wheel |\n| Pan | Right-click + drag |\n| Node info | Hover over a node |\n\n---\n\n## Adding a New Topology\n\n1. Add a generator function in `src/topologies.ts` that returns `{ nodes: NodeConfig[], links: LinkDef[] }`.\n2. Add a `TopologyMeta` entry in the `TOPOLOGIES` array in `src/topologyMeta.ts` with the topology id, name, description, feature rows, and a reference to your generator.\n3. The sidebar and info panel will pick it up automatically.\n\n### Generator example\n\n```ts\n// src/topologies.ts\nexport function generateMyTopology(): TopologyData {\n  const nodes: NodeConfig[] = [\n    { id: 'a', label: 'A', type: 'router', position: { x: 0, y: 0, z: 0 } },\n    { id: 'b', label: 'B', type: 'switch', position: { x: 3, y: 0, z: 0 } },\n  ]\n  const links: LinkDef[] = [\n    { sourceId: 'a', targetId: 'b' },\n  ]\n  return { nodes, links }\n}\n```\n\n### Metadata entry example\n\n```ts\n// src/topologyMeta.ts  — add to the TOPOLOGIES array\n{\n  id: 'my-topology',\n  name: 'My Topology',\n  subtitle: 'A custom topology',\n  description: 'Short description shown in the right panel.',\n  features: [\n    { label: 'Type',    value: 'Direct, regular' },\n    { label: 'Nodes',   value: '2' },\n  ],\n  generate: () => generateMyTopology(),\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\n```\nmain.ts\n  ├─ creates THREE.Scene, Camera, WebGLRenderer\n  ├─ adds lighting (AmbientLight, DirectionalLight, PointLight)\n  ├─ instantiates NetworkGraph(scene)\n  │     ├─ NetworkGraph       — Map<id, NetworkNode>, NetworkLink[]; supports clear()\n  │     ├─ NetworkNode        — THREE.Mesh + label Sprite; setStatus()\n  │     └─ NetworkLink        — THREE.Line; update() syncs positions each frame\n  ├─ instantiates TopologySelector  — sidebar; fires onSelect(id) callback\n  ├─ instantiates TopologyInfo      — right panel; show(TopologyMeta)\n  ├─ loadTopology(id)               — clears graph, runs generator, rebuilds scene\n  ├─ instantiates Tooltip           — fixed <div> for hover info via Raycaster\n  └─ runs the animation loop (requestAnimationFrame)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n| Symptom | Fix |\n|---------|-----|\n| Blank screen | Check browser console for errors; ensure `npm install` was run |\n| `Cannot find module 'three/addons/...'` | Run `npm install` — `@types/three` must be installed |\n| TypeScript errors on `build` | Run `npm run dev` first to confirm the runtime works, then review type errors |\n| Very low FPS | Reduce `devicePixelRatio` in `main.ts` or lower shadow map size |\n| `CMD.EXE` / UNC path error on `npm install` | You are running the Windows `npm` against a WSL path. Open a **WSL terminal** and run `npm install` from there |\n\n---\n\n## License\n\nMIT\n"
                  }
                }
              }
            },
